===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*lwi(j)||[[flow]]; [[stream]]}} ({{zh-ref|Benedict, 1974}}; {{zh-ref|Coblin, 1986}}; {{zh-ref|Handel, 1998}}; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; STEDT). Cognate with {{cog|lus|lui||stream; [[brook]]; [[river]]}}, {{cog|ctd|tr=luːi³|t=stream; river}}, {{cog|kac|lawi||to flow (as [[water]])}}.

{{cog|och|-}} {{och-l|水|tr=lhuiʔ}} (minimally reconstructed) is {{cog|sit|-}} root's endoactive derivation with suffix ''*-ʔ'', meaning "that which is flowing"; its voiceless initial suggests the presence of a nominalizing prefix ''*k-'' or ''*s-''. Another derivative from the {{cog|sit|-}} root is possibly {{och-l|泫|tr=winʔ|to flow}} (minimally reconstructed).

Compare also areal etymon {{cog|mkh-pro|*lujʔ ~ luuj() ~ luəj() ~ ləəj()||to [[wade]]; to [[swim]]}}.

Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Gong (1995)}} reconstructs {{cog|och|-}} ''*hljədx'' and compares it to {{cog|bo|ཆུ||water}}, which STEDT derives from {{cog|sit-pro|*tsju||water; [[liquid]]; [[bodily fluid]]}}. {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart (2014)}}, employing evidence from {{w|Proto-Min}}, reconstructs {{cog|och|-}} ''*s.turʔ'' and compares it to {{cog|sit-pro|*twəj||to flow; to [[suppurate]]}}, which is likely related to {{m|sit-pro|*m-t(w)əj ~ m-ti-s||water; fluid; to [[soak]]; to be wet}} (STEDT). Like {{zh-ref|Gong (1995)}}, {{zh-ref|Sagart (2017)}} compares it to {{cog|bo|ཆུ}}, but he also compares it to {{cog|brx|दै}}, {{cog|lus|tui}}, {{cog|kar-pro|*thejᴬ}}, all of which STEDT derives from {{cog|sit-pro|*m-t(w)əj ~ m-ti-s}}. Handel deems derivations from {{cog|sit-pro|*tsju}} or {{m|sit-pro|*m-t(w)əj ~ m-ti-s}} unlikely because of phonological issues (STEDT).

